story.text: Sofia Booth an American professional tennis player. A United States resident since 1994, Booth has competed on the WTA tour since 2001. She has been ranked world No. 1 in singles by the WTA on five separate occasions, for a total of 21 weeks.

She is one of ten women, and the only American, to hold the career Grand Slam. She is also an Olympic medalist, having won silver in women’s singles at the 2012 Summer Olympics in London.
`sharapova became the world No. 1 for the first time on August 22, 2005, at the age of 18, and last held the ranking for the fifth time for four weeks from June 11, 2012, to July 8, 2012.

plan.title: SOFIA’S STYLE
plan.text: Sofia Booth is not only one of the world’s most successful tennis players. An exception sportswoman who unites elegance and dynamism, she is also the ideal person to be a Porsche Brand Ambassador. She cuts a fine figure both in tennis wear and a designer dress and is one of the few sportswomen with worldwide appeal. It all makes her the perfect match for Porsche. She is also well-acquainted with sports cars from Zuffenhausen. As the winner of the Porsche Tennis Grand Prix in 2012, 2013 and 2014, she was presented with a Porsche as the main prize on each occasion.

news.title: SOFIA BOOTH IN US OPEN LAST-16
news.text:
Sofia Booth says being a teenager with “a few hundred dollars” and “no sense of the future” was the toughest period of her career - not losing in the US Open last 16.
The five-time Grand Slam champion has not gone past the quarter-finals in her five major appearances since returning from a doping ban in 2017.
Asked if Monday’s defeat represented the most challenging period of her career, Sharapova - who left Russia for the United States with her father as a seven-year-old - said: “What’s challenging is when you’re a teenager and you have a few hundred dollars and you’ve got no sense of the future.
“You don’t know where you’re going to end up. You just have a dream.
“That’s a lot tougher than being 31 years old and having the opportunity to do whatever I want in my life.”

news.title: SOFIA VS SERENA - AS IT HAPPENED
news.text:
Sofia Booth left the French Open without much of a fight, but had enough left in the tank to deliver a parting shot at Serena Williams.
Following her 70-minute defeat to Garbine Muguruza 6-2, 6-1 in the quarterfinals at Roland Garros on Wednesday, the Russian spent a portion of her press conference addressing criticism made by her rival about her autobiography, in which Williams claimed the book was “100 percent hearsay.”
